Response
I will be use venues data from Foursquare, as in the
labs. Will use the venues data from the 3 cities, merge
and group them by venue frequencies. Geocode
(location data) from geocoder python library, and
maybe geopy as well.
The zip codes of Tokyo can be obtained here (yet to ex
periment, but looks valid) - https://www.post.japanpost
jp/zipcode/dl/roman/ken_all rome.zip?190712.

For the comparison, I will make a K-means clustering
for the merged data, and analyze the number of venues
in each cluster per each city. For example, if the
number of venues in a certain cluster is close (say 5
for New York, and 4 for Toronto, where 1 for Tokyo)
for two cities, this can be sign of a similarity between
the two. I'll look at all the clusters in the same manner
and calculate the difference in number of venues for all
clusters and define it as the similarity score between
the cities.

Optionally, will analyze what the actual differences
(top 5-10) and seek what is missing or what is the
possible opportunity of venues that can be developed
to become more similar to the other cities (without
bias on which city is better and set as ideal).



